{
	"nodes":[
		{"id":"8679c50ba9608271","type":"text","text":"# Vector Quantization (Edit-distance)\n\nThe Edit-distance baseline requires discrete symbolic sequences rather than continuous coordinates. Each trajectory is converted into a string of cluster labels via k-means.\n\n## 1) Clustering procedure\nFor each fold, k-means is fit on all **training** gesture points (pooled across gestures and users), random seed = 42. Tested cluster counts $K \\in \\{15, 20, 25, 30, 35, 40\\}$. Each point is then assigned to the nearest centroid → gesture becomes a string of symbols (e.g. A→A→B→C→...).\n\n## 2) Compression (optional)\nConsecutive duplicate symbols are collapsed (e.g. A→A→B becomes A→B), reducing sensitivity to repetitive sub-gestures. Tested as binary: enabled / disabled.\n\n---\n#edit-distance #vector-quantization #kmeans #discretization #symbolic-sequences\n> Ref: [[Papers/Levenshtein1966|Levenshtein (1966)]] — edit distance definition · [[Papers/Nyirarugira2014|Nyirarugira (2014)]] — gesture-specific edit distance","x":1480,"y":-640,"width":484,"height":700},
		{"id":"eafff8569403bb92","type":"text","text":"# Cross-validation & Hyperparameter Selection\n\nTwo complementary protocols assess user-independence and within-user generalization.\n\n## User-independent evaluation (LOUO)\nLeave-one-user-out: 10 folds, each holding out all gestures from one subject. Yields 10 accuracy measurements per (method, domain, config).\n\n## User-dependent evaluation (LOSO)\nLeave-one-gesture-sample-out: for each user and gesture type, hold out one repetition; train on the other 9. Repeated 10 times.\n\n## Nested validation for hyperparameter selection\nWithin each outer fold, the training set is split 80/20 into $\\mathcal{D}_{\\text{inner-train}}$ and $\\mathcal{D}_{\\text{inner-val}}$. All preprocessing statistics and method parameters are fitted **exclusively** on $\\mathcal{D}_{\\text{inner-train}}$. The outer test fold is never seen during tuning → unbiased performance estimate.\n\n## Hyperparameter grid search\n- **Edit-distance**: $K \\in \\{15,20,25,30,35,40\\}$, compression $\\in$ {True, False}, $k \\in \\{1,3,5,7\\}$\n- **DTW**: $k \\in \\{1,3,5,7\\}$\n- **Three-Cents**: $n_{\\text{points}} \\in \\{16,32,64\\}$\n- **BiLSTM**: $T \\in \\{16,32,64\\}$, $h \\in \\{16,32,64\\}$\n- **PCA**: $n_{\\text{components}} \\in \\{\\text{none}, 2, 3\\}$ (all methods except BiLSTM)\n\n---\n#cross-validation #louo #loso #hyperparameter-tuning #nested-cv #data-leakage\n> Ref: [[Concepts/Cross_Validation|Cross-Validation Protocol]] · [[Papers/Demsar2006_StatisticalComparisons|Demšar (2006)]] — CV-based statistical comparison framework","x":2240,"y":-680,"width":880,"height":1100},
		{"id":"0d43027efc6ac049","type":"text","text":"# Classification & Distance Metrics\n\n## k-Nearest Neighbors (k-NN)\nDTW and Edit-distance use k-NN classification. For each test gesture, distances to all training gestures are computed; the test gesture is assigned the majority-vote label among its $k$ nearest neighbors. Tested $k \\in \\{1,3,5,7\\}$.\n\n## Distance computation\n| Method | Distance metric |\n|---|---|\n| DTW | Accumulated DP distance $D(N,M)$ |\n| Edit-distance | Levenshtein edit distance (DP) |\n| Three-Cents | Average point-to-point Euclidean distance |\n| BiLSTM | Softmax probability (cross-entropy loss) |\n\n## Three-Cents — 1-NN\nBy design uses 1-nearest-neighbor; $k$ is fixed at 1.\n\n---\n#knn #dtw #edit-distance #three-cents #bilstm #distance-metrics\n> Ref: [[Project - Gesture Recognition/01_DTW_Dynamic_Time_Warping|DTW]] · [[Project - Gesture Recognition/02_Edit_Distance|Edit Distance]] · [[Project - Gesture Recognition/03_Three_Cent_Recognizer|Three-Cents]] · [[Project - Gesture Recognition/04_BiLSTM|BiLSTM]]","x":1737,"y":520,"width":560,"height":620},
		{"id":"2e6e9ea172c9f8c4","type":"text","text":"# Ablation Study\n\nSystematically isolates the contribution of each preprocessing decision by varying one component at a time while holding all others fixed.\n\n## What is varied\n- **Normalization**: applied or not\n- **PCA**: $n_{\\text{components}} \\in \\{\\text{none}, 2, 3\\}$\n\n→ **80 configurations** total (4 methods × 2 domains × 2 CV modes × 5 preprocessing combos)\n\n## Purpose\n- Attribute accuracy changes unambiguously to a single component\n- Reveal interactions between preprocessing steps\n- Assess robustness of each classifier to implementation choices\n\n## Key findings\n- **Normalization** is quasi-universally beneficial, especially in user-independent mode (+1.5 to +20.8 pp for DTW, +3.2 pp for BiLSTM in user-dependent)\n- **PCA improves only when combined with normalization** — applying PCA to raw data can degrade performance (edit-distance, domain 4)\n- **Three-Cents** is robust to preprocessing: its internal invariances (resample–scale–translate) already absorb amplitude and position variability\n- **BiLSTM** is the most sensitive to normalization: input scale affects gradient stability during training\n\n---\n#ablation #preprocessing #normalization #pca #evaluation #robustness\n> Ref: [[Papers/Demsar2006_StatisticalComparisons|Demšar (2006)]] — statistical comparison framework · [[Papers/Srivastava2014_Dropout|Srivastava et al. (2014)]] — BiLSTM regularisation · [[Papers/Caputo2018_3DGestures|Caputo et al. (2018)]] — preprocessing benchmarks on 3D gestures","x":900,"y":520,"width":680,"height":760},
		{"id":"f3ca2afb325af4df","type":"text","text":"# Preprocessing\n\nAll gestures were loaded from the raw data files and preprocessed in a consistent manner across methods. The preprocessing pipeline consisted of three main steps :\n\n## 1) Normalization\nEach gesture trajectory was normalized using standardization (z-score normalization) computed **exclusively on the training set** to prevent data leakage. For each fold, the mean µ and standard deviation σ were calculated from all training gesture points, and then applied uniformly to both training and test sets.\n\nThis removes scale and location artifacts, ensuring that all methods operate on gesture trajectories with zero mean and unit variance.\n\n## 2) Dimensionality reduction (optional)\nPCA was optionally applied to the training set before classification. PCA was fit only on the training data; the resulting transformation was then applied to both sets. Tested with $n_{\\text{components}} \\in \\{2, 3\\}$ and no-PCA baseline. Applied point-wise for variable-length trajectories.\n\n## 3) Variable-length handling\nGesture trajectories exhibit variable length. Methods requiring fixed-length input (Three-Cents, BiLSTM) use resampling. DTW and Edit-distance handle variable-length sequences natively.\n\n---\n#preprocessing #normalization #pca #data-leakage #z-score\n> Ref: [[Papers/Ioffe2015_BatchNorm|Ioffe & Szegedy (2015)]] — normalization theory · [[Papers/Deisenroth2020_MML|Deisenroth et al. (2020)]] — PCA","x":540,"y":-560,"width":700,"height":860}
	],
